We can inspect an array in many different ways. One of the methods is to use attributes. For instance, shape : get the dimension of an array size : get the total number of values in the array dtype : get the type of the values in the array Previously we have created a random array. We will use that array to visualize the attributes. First, let's recall the data array. In [10]: Copied! data data Out[10]: array([['4', '5', '6'], ['7', '8', '9'], ['a', 'b', 'c'], ['1.0', '2.0', '3.33']], dtype='<U32') Not, let's display those attributes. In [11]: Copied! # Attributes a = data . shape b = data . size c = data . dtype # Print the result print ( f " shape: { a } 
 size: { b } 
 dtype: { c } " ) # Attributes a = data.shape b = data.size c = data.dtype # Print the result print(f" shape: {a}
 size: {b}
 dtype: {c}") shape: (4, 3) size: 12 dtype: <U32 As we can see above, the shape of the data array is 3x4. It has 1 value in the array and the values have a type of <U32 . A <U32 stands for the set of lower case Unicode 32 character

Slicing is used for getting values out of a NumPy array, for example data[0] : to get the first array data[0:2] : get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2 data[-1] : get the last array data[2][1][0] : get the first value ( [0] ) of the array [1] and [2] In [12]: Copied! # Slicing array = data [ 0 ] # get the first array slicer = data [ 0 : 2 ] # get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2 reverse = data [ - 1 ] # get the last array single_value = data [ 2 ][ 1 ][ 0 ] # get the first value ([0]) of the array [1] and [2] # Print the result print ( f " array: { array } 
 slicer: { slicer } 
 reverse: { reverse } 
 single_value: { single_value } " ) # Slicing array = data[0] # get the first array slicer = data[0:2] # get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2 reverse = data[-1] # get the last array single_value = data[2][1][0] # get the first value ([0]) of the array [1] and [2] # Print the result print(f" array: {array}
 slicer: {slicer}
 reverse: {reverse}
 single_value: {single_value}") array: ['4' '5' '6'] slicer: [['4' '5' '6'] ['7' '8' '9']] reverse: ['1.0' '2.0' '3.33'] single_value: b

